.TH indicator 1F "5 Jul 1990" "SunOS 5.11" "FMLI Commands"
.SH NAME
indicator \- display application specific alarms and/or the "working"
indicator
.SH SYNOPSIS
.LP
.nf
\fBindicator\fR [\fB-b\fR [\fIn\fR]] [\fB-c\fR \fIcolumn\fR] [\fB-l\fR \fIlength\fR] [\fB-o\fR] [\fB-w\fR]
     [\fIstring\fR]...
.fi

.SH DESCRIPTION
.sp
.LP
The \fBindicator\fR function displays application specific alarms or the
"working" indicator, or both, on the  \fBFMLI\fR banner line. The argument
\fIstring\fR is a string to be displayed on the banner line, and should
always be the last argument given. Note that \fIstring\fR is not
automatically cleared from the banner line.
.SH OPTIONS
.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
\fB\fB-b\fR\fIn\fR\fR
.ad
.RS 13n
.rt
The \fB-b\fR option rings the terminal bell \fIn\fR times, where \fIn\fR is
an integer from 1 to 10. The default value is 1. If the terminal has no
bell, the screen is flashed instead, if possible.
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
\fB\fB\fR\fB-c\fR\fB \fR\fIcolumn\fR\fR
.ad
.RS 13n
.rt
The \fB-c\fR option defines the column of the banner line at which to start
the indicator string. The argument \fIcolumn\fR  must be an integer from
\fB0\fR to \fBDISPLAYW-1.\fR If the \fB-c\fR option is not used,
\fIcolumn\fR defaults to \fB0 .\fR
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
\fB\fB\fR\fB-l\fR\fB \fR\fIlength\fR\fR
.ad
.RS 13n
.rt
The \fB-l\fR option defines the maximum length of the string displayed. If
\fIstring\fR is longer than \fIlength\fR characters, it will be truncated.
The argument \fIlength\fR must be an integer from \fB1\fR to \fBDISPLAYW.\fR
If the \fB-l\fR option is not used, \fIlength\fR defaults to \fBDISPLAYW.\fR
Note that if \fIstring\fR doesn't fit it will be truncated.
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
\fB\fB-o\fR\fR
.ad
.RS 13n
.rt
The \fB-o\fR option causes \fBindicator\fR to duplicate its output to
\fIstdout\fR \fI\&.\fR
.RE

.sp
.ne 2
.mk
.na
\fB\fB-w\fR\fR
.ad
.RS 13n
.rt
The \fB-w\fR option turns on the "working" indicator.
.RE

.SH EXAMPLES
.LP
\fBExample 1 \fRA sample output of the \fBindicator\fR command.
.sp
.LP
When the value entered in a form field is invalid, the following use of
\fBindicator\fR will ring the bell three times and display the word
\fBWRONG\fR starting at column 1 of the banner line.

.sp
.in +2
.nf
\fBinvalidmsg=`indicator \fR\fB-b\fR 3 \fB-c\fR 1 "WRONG"`
.fi
.in -2
.sp

.sp
.LP
To clear the indicator after telling the user the entry is wrong:

.sp
.in +2
.nf
\fBinvalidmsg=`indicator \fR\fB-b\fR\fB 9 \fR\fB-c\fR\fB 1 "WRONG"; sleep 3;
        indicator \fR\fB-c\fR\fB 1 "     "`\fR
.fi
.in -2
.sp

.sp
.LP
In this example the value of \fBinvalidmsg\fR (in this case the default
value \fBInput is not valid\fR), still appears on the  \fBFMLI\fR message
line. 

